<subSubSection pageId="19" pageNumber="220" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="19.[151,1437,402,1153]" pageId="19" pageNumber="220">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,428,402,427]" pageId="19" pageNumber="220">Diagnostic description.</emphasis>
Defined by the following combination of characters: (1) MF DFW white apical ocelli small. (2) MF DFW orange band wide, orange scales extended proximally along veins, including the anterior tip of discal cell. (3) M DFW iridescent band absent or barely visible at tornus only. F DFW iridescent band shorter, more diffuse and narrower than that of 
<taxonomicName box="[522,617,511,534]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Bia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="19" pageNumber="220" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="actorion">
<emphasis box="[522,617,511,534]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="220">actorion</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, especially noticeable below CuA2 where the iridescence is less extended towards the tornus. (4) DFW androconial organ on Cu-CuA2 pale, contrasting scale color of surrounding area. (5) M DHW discal androconial pad cream-colored. (6) M DHW discal hairpencil pale brown to cream-colored. (7) F VFW ripple pattern usually slightly less dense than that of M, with the VFW postmedial area showing a more predominantly yellow color.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="19" pageNumber="220" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="19.[151,1437,402,1153]" pageId="19" pageNumber="220">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,696,721]" pageId="19" pageNumber="220">Etymology.</emphasis>
Cuprum is the Latin word for copper, which is used in reference to the fact that males of 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Bia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="19" pageNumber="220" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" species="rebeli" subSpecies="cuprea">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="220">rebeli cuprea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
lack blue iridescence, being only orange and brown dorsally.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
